Any methods in the `Composite` class that use the `Component` object should be accessed through the public interface of the `Composite` class. This encapsulates the implementation details of the `Component` object within the `Composite` class, which promotes code reuse and modularity.

In general, it's a good practice to declare the fields of a composition as private members to ensure that they can only be accessed from within the containing class. This helps to prevent coupling between objects and promotes a more modular and robust code design.

